63-66. Tib. begins his argument that poetry immortalizes by enforcing the negative (63-64), ae. ‘without poetry all would be forgotten': so too Pind. Nem. 7, 12-16; 9, 6; Hor. Od.4,9,25; Propert. 3, 2, 15; Tac. Agric.46; Sil. Ital. 3,145; etc.
